The whole tax thing is weird to me. On the surface, the Left saying that those with more money should pay more taxes in order to benefit those with less money makes sense but, as with most things on the Left, when you look more closely it falls apart. I mean, first off, you paying more taxes means you have to trust the Government to actually use those taxes properly. People see stuff like "we will spend $2bn on building new affordable homes" and they think "great"! But when it comes to building those "new affordable homes" Governments almost always waste their $2bn with expensive contracts on projects which never quite come to fruition and so on. And who is benefiting from these construction contracts? Well, who knows really. It used to be the Mafia in New York, which probably says it all about how dodgy construction contracts are. Why do people think that rich people, high earners, are automatically taking money out of the pockets of poor people? These high earners tend to keep money in circulation, they buy and sell property, they provide jobs, they invest, they help fuel the economy - all of which benefits those who are less well off. If you say to these high earners that they must give over 60% of their income to the Government, you are basically diverting their money away from being spent in their communities, in the economy, toward a Government who generally wastes it. I'm British, so I can't give direct examples in the US (but I'm sure you've all seen them) but let me give you an example from over here in London. We give our taxes to both Government and local councils so that they will spend a proportion on improving our roads and, supposedly, reducing our emissions. I live in an area of London called Islington (run by Labour incidentally, the British Democrats) and there is a major intersection in the area known as Highbury Roundabout, where 4 main thoroughfares come together. The traffic has always been busy there, but it always used to flow reasonable well. About 10 years ago they decided to "improve" this intersection. They redesigned the road layout and got to work. It took them a full year to complete, causing all sorts of congestion in the meantime. Having completed the construction they then decided more maintenance needed doing and they began a whole new project on the same spot, probably taking another year to complete. Once that was done they seemed to decide their new road layout was no good for cyclists or something, so they tore it up and put it back how it was before, taking another however long. Long story short, the intersection has been changed multiple times, it is now an ENTIRELY new layout with empty cycle lanes taking up half the road space, 10 years later they are STILL doing construction there and traffic (thus emissions) is worse than ever. This is what they want to increase our taxes for? I would have preferred to not give them the money, forcing them to stick to 1 plan, and leave the rich folk (who have very little direct impact on my life) to spend their money and boost our economy personally. I don't really understand why the Left hates on private business wealth so much and yet endorses flushing money down the Government drain, fattening the pockets of bureaucrats and politicians instead? Then I look at charities. In my opinion, charities do FAR more for the needy than the Government, and most of the biggest philanthropists happen to be those wealthy folk you want taxed at over 60%! What do you think happens to those donations? I can tell you that, when a high earner is spending a large portion of his income on his extortionate expenses, and when much of his excess he gives to charities, it won't be his expenses which lose out when the taxman comes knocking.

I walked away from family years ago and it wasn't because of politics or even religious beliefs.  It was because of insanity.  Sometimes you have to step back and really assess the effects your family are having on your life.  It can be ugly and they will make every effort to make you feel guilty but sometimes, cutting yourself off from the rest, is the only solution.  Once I stepped away and moved on my life became so much richer and happy.  After a time I realized how much stress and aggravation the family had caused me.  I was fortunate in that my spouse and son felt the same way.  So the three of us moved on as our own family and it was great.  The son is grown now and living his own life and we are a part of his life.  The three of us have a wonderful relationship; but when we were engaged in the extended family, our relationship was strained.  It is hard, because of course you love your family; but some people can not be reasoned with.  Some people can not help but inflict emotional turbulence onto you.  We had to make a choice.   We do not regret that choice.  If family would express hate and or anger to you because of a political choice you have made; all I can suggest is that you seriously assess your family.  Something is slightly off-kilter there.  Seriously think about it.  What kind of family would hate or get angry at you for a political choice?  Sometimes your family can be more of an enemy to you than a stranger.  I read an article, years ago, by a well known (at the time) psychiatrist.  In the article she explained, family that tries to manipulate and control you through emotions; try to make you feel guilty; try to make you feel responsibility and duty to them, are in fact, turning you into an 'emotional hostage'.  That article really opened my eyes and it was one of the things that gave me the strength I needed to pull away and live my own life.  Good luck to all of you having to suffer the emotional out-casting of your family.  Life is short, if you don't make your life a happy one, you will die an emotional. bitter, wreck.

So, for the record, top marginal rates do not affect your ENTIRE income, only that which falls into the top bracket of earnings

For example, say the top marginal tax rate is 40%, and the top bracket is income levels of $400,000 and above. Say you make $500,000. You wouldn't have a nominal tax obligation of $200,000. Rather, it would be the amount paid based whatever the rate is for the brackets of income up TO the $400k threshold (the lower brackets have substantially lower tax rates), plus $20,000 (which is 40% of the $100,000 of income that is between the $400,000 threshold for the top bracket and your actual income). It's a difference of tens of thousands of dollars.

Obviously, everyone feels differently about what the rates are, and the specific levels at which what the different brackets are set. I'm not arguing one way or another about that. I just think it's important to be clear about how the progressive tax system works.

The tax rate affects the portion of your tax that enters that tax bracket.

Example: you make 100k, if there are 3 tax brackets that you cross into 0-20k 20-60k and 60-100+k and each has a particular tax rate. You pay that rate for the first 20k, then the next 40k gets taxed at the second bracket rate, then the third bracket rate covers the rest of it. So you don't actually make less money for breaking into the next tax bracket.

Definitely not saying I'm in favor of any of these taxes but its best not to spread misinformation. Getting a raise that pushes you into a new tax bracket will not cause you to make less money after taxes.

For those of you who are retiring, consider leaving your money in your 401-K plan (if you can), and draw it out slowly to supplement your income. If you can live off the compound interest only, your money will last forever and work for you when you quit working. Make sure you know where the line is concerning the tax rates and where you fall. I made a ton of money in my plan with the experts running it, why would I change that if I don't have to? If it ain't broke, don't fix it!

It's critical that you choose the right plan, at the right time (ASAP), and contribute AT LEAST what they match, but max it out when you can! My motto is, "Live on 1/2 of what you make, save and invest the rest!"

Another consideration is, when you turn 65 and sign up for Medicare, Medicare goes back 2 years to determine how much to charge you for their services. It's variable every two years (I think). Example, if you choose to downsize and sell your house when you're 63, Medicare will consider that as your income and charge you accordingly when you turn 65 two years later. Selling when you're 62 may be a better plan and could save you money in the long run.

One more pearl......when you die and your kids inherit your 401-K, they MAY not have to draw it out all at once. They can leave it in, and draw it out at a minimum of $10,000 a year. By leaving it in for as long as they can, they can supplement their income, and continue to enjoy the compound interest which hopefully, is what you were doing. Teach your children how to handle their money.
